snippet.textDisplay:
As a former high school theatre kid and current theatre major I take issue with your ranking of types of theatre kids; acting kids and improv kids should be separate. Now, any theatre kid can be annoying, you can get a techie talking for two hours about the different lighting fixtures, but it's much harder.
1 - Stage crew, they are the least annoying, mostly sleep in various areas of the theatre. Do not get them talking about power tools.
2 - Acting/Straight Play kids - On the off chance you mention that one play no one without a theatre degree even knows about that they adore they won't shut up, but you're probably fine around them. Do keep an eye on your school's season, do not bring up any straight play that's been done at that school in their time their, though.
3 - Musical kids - Will manufacture a way to bring up basically any musical "Is that a Hamilton sticker? No? Just a star? WELL have you listened to it?", does not shut up, sings during class hoping for compliments. Talking about the founding of America? "Did you know Hamilton-" Talking about the 1920s? "WELL in Chicago and Throughly Modern Millie-" There is no way to avoid the obsession. Same rule about not bringing up the musicals your school has done in their time.
4 - Improv kids, you are absolutely right about improv kids. Will invite you to their interactive improv show. Will invite you six times a day. Will explain the yes and rule at least a dozen times. Thinks they are God's gift to comedy. They are decidedly not.

snippet.textDisplay: The theater program at my rural high school was so small that we were all set builders/stage crew, musical kids, and acting/improv kids at one time or another. There were like 5 people total who were designated stage managers or lights/sound crew because they had no interest in acting. We always had a Fall play and a Spring musical (we only did a Winter one-act once before we collectively vetoed it altogether), so pretty much everyone had a chance to be in one or the other. If you didn't make the cast, you were a crew member and everyone was pretty happy with it. Way more chill than any other high school theater program I've heard of.
